links.title: Beyond Meat plunges following surprise loss on 'full brunt of COVID'
links.description: Shares of Beyond Meat ( BYND) are under pressure after the company reported worse than expected quarterly results amid a slowdown in the pace of sales growth caused by the pandemic. Despite the news, Piper Sandler analyst Michael Lavery upgraded the stock to Overweight, while his peer at UBS raised Beyond Meat's rating to Neutral.

messages.body:
$BYND posted a surprise loss due to COVID toll on the restaurant and food services industry.

31 cents per share. That is only 2.7% growth year over year, not good!
CEO Ethan Brown mentioned first-quarter earnings were strong because everyone loaded up and stockpiled food. When real meat was not available during the lockdown, you could still buy BYND meat in stores. 

It has been a rollercoaster ride for shares in just the last two days. Prices gapped higher on Monday, then fell 13% intraday, and then rallied back 20% late in the day on a partnership deal with McDonald's. Price still ended lower after all of those price swings heading into the earnings last night.

I think $MCD will not only boost sales but add a layer of more stable revenue for BYND.

The partnership will also help them stay ahead of the fierce competition from Impossible Foods, Planterra Foods, and Prime Roots.
Shares today are down 30%, but shares hit a technical support level at $114 earlier today and are bouncing.
